I have a .NET 4.5 WPF application that directly accesses a MS SQL database via Entity Framework 6.2. The app runs perfectly fine on most computers of our customer, however there is one system where our app cannot access the database because EF creates SQL statements internally that reference a table that does not exist:

&gt; System.Data.Entity.Core.EntityCommandExecutionException: An error occurred while executing the command definition. See the inner exception for details. ---&gt;
&gt; System.Data.SqlClient.SqlException: **Invalid object name &#39;dbo.Configurations&#39;.**

Our configuration entity looks like this:

    using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;
    using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations.Schema;

    namespace SomeNamespace
    {
        [Table(&quot;Configuration&quot;)]
        public class Configuration : EntityBase
        {
            [Required]
            [MaxLength(50)]
            public string Name { get; set; }

            public string Value { get; set; }

            [Required]
            public string Username { get; set; }
        }
    }

Our DbContext class looks like this (excerpt):

    public class SomeContext : DbContext
    {
        public virtual DbSet&lt;Configuration&gt; Configurations { get; set; }
        
        protected override void OnModelCreating(DbModelBuilder modelBuilder)
        {
            Database.SetInitializer&lt;SomeContext&gt;(null);
            base.OnModelCreating(modelBuilder);
        }
    }

**Why is the `TableAttribute` ignored by EF on some systems?** To me, it&#39;s obvious that EF does not respect the `TableAttribute` in this case because it wants to access the `dbo.Configurations` table (derived from the Configurations property of the DbContext) instead of `dbo.Configuration` using the name from the attribute. **The funny thing is that this only happens on one computer** - on all other ones, the app just runs fine.

I suspected that an older version of EF is installed in the GAC which is loaded instead of the EF DLL that I deploy with our app - thus I set **Specific Version** to true in the project references (Entity Framework was not added to the project via NuGet). This did not solve the problem.

I think that a quick solution would be to not use attributes but the fluent API instead. However, does anybody know why this problem occurs in the first place?

